data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span` of native-sized integers.** Both `nint` and `nuint` work:

```csharp
Span<nint> span = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

As confirmed by the test output, `nint` maps to `IntPtr` and `nuint` maps to `UIntPtr` at runtime. The allocation, indexing, and iteration all work as expected. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 (when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types).
